{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017xUBCUHKo3aAUU5t3Uj1KK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the bug.\n\nThe function `_yr_scan_wicompare` in `libyara/scan.c` at line 199 is comparing a wide (UTF-16 LE) string against a narrow (ASCII/single-byte) string.\n\nIn UTF-16 LE encoding, each character takes 2 bytes. For ASCII characters, the encoding is: character byte followed by `0x00`. For example, 'c' in UTF-16 LE is `0x63 0x00`.\n\nThe function traverses `s1` by 2 (`s1+=2`) because it's iterating over wide characters (2 bytes each), and `s2` by 1 (`s2++`) because it's iterating over narrow characters.\n\n\nThe real issue is that the buggy version dropped the check ensuring the second byte of each wide character is `0x00`, which is critical for validating that we're dealing with actual ASCII characters in wide form. Without this validation, strings with non-ASCII wide characters like `0x63 0xFF 0x6D 0xFF...` would incorrectly match against narrow strings they shouldn't match. narrow string \"cm...\" because the second bytes (0xFF) are ignored.\n\nThis is precisely what issue #1006 was about - the fix added that check to prevent false positives when matching wide strings case-insensitively, and the buggy commit reverted that fix.\n\nThe test at line 1420 (`assert_false_rule_blob`) checks that `\" cmd.exe \" nocase wide` does NOT match `ISSUE_1006` - the blob likely contains something that looks like \"cmd.exe\" when the second byte check is skipped.\n\nROOT CAUSE: `libyara/scan.c:199` — the `*(s1 + 1) == 0x00` condition was removed from the `_yr_scan_wicompare` while loop. This condition checks that the high byte of each UTF-16 LE wide character is zero (i.e., it's a basic ASCII character), preventing false positive matches against wide strings that contain non-ASCII characters.\n\nFor the immediate fix, I need to restore that byte validation check in the while condition so it properly validates both bytes of each UTF-16 LE character. A more robust long-term solution would be to refactor the comparison logic with an explicit UTF-16 LE decoder function that makes the character validation unmistakable, or add targeted unit tests for this function that specifically exercise non-ASCII wide strings to catch regressions like this.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1132,"cache_read_input_tokens":27073,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1132},"output_tokens":10,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a5b18b46-9e82-46b5-bead-3014f5df4f75","uuid":"5011bd36-0336-462f-b6e6-a448b82f1f44"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017xUBCUHKo3aAUU5t3Uj1KK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have a complete picture of the bug. The diff shows exactly what was changed.\n\nThe function `_yr_scan_wicompare` (line 185) compares a wide (UTF-16 LE) string against a narrow ASCII string. In UTF-16 LE, each ASCII character is stored as two bytes: the character byte followed by `0x00`. The loop steps through `s1` two bytes at a time (`s1+=2`) but compares only the first byte of each wide character with the narrow character.\n\nThe original correct code at line 199 was:\n```c\nwhile (i < string_length &&\n       yr_lowercase[*s1] == yr_lowercase[*s2] &&\n       *(s1 + 1) == 0x00)\n```\n\nThe buggy commit removed `*(s1 + 1) == 0x00`, leaving:\n```c\nwhile (i < string_length && yr_lowercase[*s1] == yr_lowercase[*s2])\n```\n\nWithout the `*(s1 + 1) == 0x00` guard, a wide string whose second bytes are non-zero (i.e., non-BMP0 / non-ASCII wide characters) can falsely match a narrow search string, because only the first byte of each wide character is checked. This is exactly what issue #1006 was about — the fix was committed in `5fcbd4a0`, and the \"buggy\" commit reverted it.\n\nThe test at `test-rules.c:1420` verifies `\" cmd.exe \" nocase wide` does NOT match `ISSUE_1006`, a blob crafted to trigger this false positive. With the check removed, the rule incorrectly matches.\n\n---\n\n**ROOT CAUSE:** `libyara/scan.c:199` — the `*(s1 + 1) == 0x00` condition was removed from the `_yr_scan_wicompare` while loop. This condition verifies that the high byte of each UTF-16 LE wide character is zero (a valid BMP0/ASCII encoding), without which the function accepts non-ASCII wide bytes as false-positive matches against the narrow search string.\n\n**LOCAL FIX:** Restore the deleted condition in the while loop:\n```c\nwhile (i < string_length &&\n       yr_lowercase[*s1] == yr_lowercase[*s2] &&\n       *(s1 + 1) == 0x00)\n```\n\n**GLOBAL FIX:** Extract explicit UTF-16 LE decoding into a helper (e.g., `yr_decode_utf16le_char(const uint8_t *s, uint32_t *codepoint)`) that returns both the codepoint and whether the encoding was valid. Any wide-string comparison function would call this helper, making it structurally impossible to compare only the low byte without also validating the high byte. This eliminates the entire class of false-positive wide-string match bugs caused by silently ignoring the second byte of a UTF-16 LE code unit."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1132,"cache_read_input_tokens":27073,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1132},"output_tokens":10,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a5b18b46-9e82-46b5-bead-3014f5df4f75","uuid":"caaf7bd5-1e21-4558-b92f-e0c16a43bdf3"}
